# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wayland-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A **compositing manager**, or **compositor**, is software that provides applications with an off-screen buffer for each window, then composites these window buffers into an image representing the screen and writes the result into the display memory.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A **compositing window manager** is a window manager that is also a compositing manager.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Computer graphics technology allows for visual effects to be rendered in real time such as drop shadows, live previews, and complex animation.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Since the screen is double buffered, it does not flicker during updates.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The window manager sends each window a message to repaint itself when needed.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] When a window in front is moved, it can reveal an area of a window behind that was previously concealed.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Window managers are broadly categorised by their strategy for causing that newly revealed area to be displayed to the user.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In the "stacking" strategy, the window manager tells the back window to repaint itself.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In the "compositing" strategy, the window manager maintains an off-screen memory buffer containing the full appearance of each window, including the back window.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] With a stacking manager, the repainting process can become corrupted when a program that is slow, unresponsive or buggy does not respond to messages in a timely manner.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A malicious program can cause the system to appear unstable by simply neglecting to repaint its window.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] With a compositing manager, if a window stops repainting itself when requested by the window manager, its last repaint will remain displayed and the window might be dimmed.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Often, the title changes to reflect the status of the window as unresponsive.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A program may prevent its window from being moved or unmapped, but generally will not cause repainting problems.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The Commodore Amiga, released in 1985, was one of the first systems with a compositing windowing system.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Applications could first request a region of memory outside the current display region for use as bitmap.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The Amiga windowing system would then use a series of bit blits using the system's hardware blitter to build a composite of these applications' bitmaps - along with buttons and sliders - in display memory, without requiring these applications to redraw any of their bitmaps.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] On March 24, 2001, Apple's Mac OS X 10.0 (Cheetah) became the first mainstream operating system to feature software-based 3D compositing and effects, provided by its Quartz component.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] With the release of Mac OS X 10.2 (Jaguar) and Quartz Extreme, the job of compositing could move to dedicated graphics hardware.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In 2003 Sun Microsystems demonstrated an ambitious 3D graphics system called Project Looking Glass to layer on top of its Swing toolkit.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] It was first shown at the 2003 LinuxWorld Expo.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Although Apple threatened to sue Sun for breach of intellectual-property rights, other window managers have implemented some of the functionality in Looking Glass.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] By 2006 development was discontinued by Sun, whose primary business was transitioning from graphically oriented Unix workstations to selling enterprise mainframes.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Microsoft first presented the Desktop Window Manager in Project Longhorn to the 2003 Windows Hardware Engineering Conference, demonstrating wobbly windows.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Severe delays in the Longhorn development process caused Microsoft not to debut its 3D-compositing window-manager until the release of Windows Vista in November 2006.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Implementing compositing under the X Window System required some redesign, which took place incrementally.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Metacity 2.8.4 was released in August 2004.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] However, the first widely publicized compositing window manager for X was Xfwm, released in January 2005.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] On 26 January 2005 Compiz was released, introducing fully accelerated 3D-compositing to the Linux platform.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In compositing, 3D effects could be applied on windows to provide 3D desktop effects.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Modern compositing window managers use 3D hardware acceleration.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compositing window manager software communicates with graphics hardware via programming interfaces such as OpenGL or Direct3D.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The earliest widespread implementations using this technique were released for the Mac in Mac OS X 10.2, and for Linux in a Luminocity prototype.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Currently, window managers using OpenGL include Compiz, KWin, and the Quartz Compositor, while Desktop Window Manager currently uses DirectX 9.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] OpenGL is still not fully supported in hardware, so performance of OpenGL-based compositing should continue to improve as hardware improves.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Stacking window managers running on the X Window System (X11) required a chroma keying or green screening extension.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compositing was introduced by way of the Composite Extension.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compositing managers use hardware acceleration through this extension, if available.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Under X11, the ability to do full 3D-accelerated compositing required fundamental changes to the window system protocol in order to use hardware acceleration.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Originally, a number of modified X11 implementations designed around OpenGL began to appear, including Xgl.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The introduction of AIGLX would eliminate the need to use Xgl, and allow window managers to do 3D accelerated compositing on a standard X server, while still allowing for direct rendering.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Currently, NVIDIA, Intel, and ATI cards support AIGLX.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compiz introduced a cube effect, which allows the user to see up to 6 virtual desktops at once.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Each desktop is converted into a surface texture of the cube, which can be rotated at will.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compiz displays a wide array of 2D and 3D effects and has relatively low hardware requirements.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In 2012, Compiz was included in Ubuntu Linux, and was enabled automatically when supported hardware and drivers were available and the user had not selected 2D Mode.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Mutter (Metacity + Clutter) has replaced Metacity as the default window manager for GNOME.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] It is featured in the GNOME Shell component of GNOME 3.0.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] It uses the display engine Clutter, which has been ported to all major operating systems, netbooks and smartphones.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Since version 4, KDE's window manager KWin has compositing capabilities.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] KWin features much of the same functionality also present in Compiz.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] With the Wayland protocol, a compositing window manager is also a display server; there is no display server separate from the window manager.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The combined window manager/display server is called a Wayland compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Weston is a reference implementation of a Wayland compositor; KWin and Mutter are also Wayland compositors as well as being X11 compositing window managers.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Project Looking Glass was a window manager combining 3D rendering and the cross-platform Java programming language.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] It is now inactive and released under the GNU General Public License.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The Granular Linux live CD distribution includes Looking Glass as an optional window manager.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In the aftermath of it being discontinued, some of its features, such as cover switching and thumbnail live previews, have found their way onto other window managers.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Its more original features included window tilting, two-sided window frames and parallax scrolling backgrounds.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] While they are able to run on 3D-capable hardware, AmigaOS 4 and MorphOS are designed to run on old legacy Amiga computers, starting with the Amiga 1200.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] As such, their window managers have mostly planar rendering capabilities that include composite layering, alpha blending, gradients, high resolution and multiple desktops ("screens") that can partially clip one another.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] While the window manager in Windows 2000 does perform compositing, it does not perform transformations such as a per-pixel alpha.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Few commercial applications took advantage of alpha blending; freeware programs were among the first to experiment with it, albeit through optional settings.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compositing was introduced with Desktop Window Manager in Windows Vista.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Windows Vista and Windows 7 allow the user to disable Desktop Window Manager by selecting the Windows Basic appearance settings.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In addition, it is automatically disabled by Windows in order to perform hardware overlay through the Overlay Mixer Filter.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The compositing approach makes it easier to implement a number of features that make the user interface more accessible, simpler to use or with eye candy elements.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Vector graphics, such as TrueType fonts and 3D-accelerated elements, can be expanded without degradation (usually due to aliasing).
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A screen magnifier enlarges an area of the screen, making portions of text easier to read – whether to prevent eye strain, for the visually impaired, or simply at a distance.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Zoom effects such as the fish eye magnifier and zoom desktop effects provide this functionality.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A preview of a window can be displayed in a pop-up thumbnail when the user hovers its associated taskbar button.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] This allows the user to identify and manage several concurrently running programs.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Windows with similar names and icons tend to cause confusion, especially when their title bars overlap; the position of every such window on the taskbar has to be memorized.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] When there are many open windows in this manner, the user often has to resort to trial and error—clicking each taskbar button one-by-one—before proceeding.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Window switching allows one to quickly preview several windows at once by temporarily rearranging them against a decorative background.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] After a selection is made, the windows are then restored to their original arrangement.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Selection begins when the user either enters a hotkey combination, moves the mouse pointer to a hotspot on the screen, or, in some situations, uses the mouse's scroll wheel.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Items are navigated using the keyboard or mouse.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] An item is selected by either releasing the hotkey, hitting the Enter key or clicking on it with the mouse.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The flip switcher is an enhancement to the Alt-Tab switching feature.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Running windows are arranged into a stack – similar to a flip-style selector in a 1950s jukebox, or a Rolodex.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In some systems, the user can press Alt-Shift-Tab to navigate backwards.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Visual transitions are applied to each item while navigating.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Common implementations of flip switching include Flip 3D in Windows and Shift Switcher in Compiz.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Cover switching is like flip switching with a few, mostly visual, differences.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Instead of one stack with the selection at the top, two symmetrical stacks are shown with the current selection front and center (similar to the window tilting feature in Looking Glass).
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Cover Flow is an implementation of cover switching in macOS.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] More recent versions use blurring to de-emphasize non-selected items.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Cover Flow has also been implemented in other software published by Apple such as iTunes.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Ring switching is like flip switching, except the windows move in a circle, with the current selection in front, usually at the bottom.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Most compositing window managers include this feature out of the box, and third-party applications, such as 3d-desktop, are also available.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The user can group windows together, such that only one window at a time is visible in each group.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] In Compiz, the window frame is flipped to indicate when the active window in its group has been changed.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] macOS displays a preview of every window on the screen by tiling them.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Other systems with similar functionality (Microsoft Windows, Compiz, KWin, third-party applications) are referred to as Exposé clones.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The hotkey to activate Exposé is not Alt-Tab, but rather F3.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Mac OS X 10.7 combines several other compositing features developed by Apple—such as Exposé, Dashboard, and Spaces—into a larger program called Mission Control.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] On macOS, "widgets" (single-purpose applets) such as a clock, note pad, and calculator can appear by pressing a hotkey.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Widget engines speed work by keeping commonly used widgets accessible while unobtrusive.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] They are handled by the Dashboard program in macOS.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Compiz starts with a blank Widget Layer, allowing the user to add applications by clicking on them.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A variety of widgets are supported, including Screenlets, gDesklets and SuperKaramba.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Windows Vista provides gadgets that the user can place on the Windows Sidebar (Sidebar gadgets), a Windows Live start page (Web gadgets), or an external display, such as the user's mobile phone (SideShow gadgets).
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The Windows Sidebar was a visible partition in Windows Vista, and was eliminated in Windows 7, along with Sidebar gadgets which were changed to Desktop Gadgets.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Before compositing window managers were developed, windows would instantly jump in and out of view, which is incongruent with the interface metaphor (and with a physical office setting).
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Some systems like the Classic Mac OS avoided this issue with ZoomRects, animating the windows outline "zooming" toward its final position.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] But on most systems, the sudden appearance and disappearance of GUI elements may seem confusing or even chaotic to inexperienced users.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Visual transitions provide context and help distinguish the causal relationships of GUI elements.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Instead of just disappearing, a window may fade away, or visibly shrink to the taskbar.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] A pull-down menu that has been clicked may smoothly radiate outward from the menu bar, making it easier to determine its origin and purpose.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Gradual and natural transitions may be especially helpful for elderly or visually impaired users who notice changes to the screen more slowly and with less clarity.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] For example, an inexperienced user may impulsively click on a menu that was activated by accident, causing him or her to lose work.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] The short delay necessary to display a visual transition may give the user enough time to make a conscious decision, and avoid such mistakes.
[src:wayland-protocol/compositing-window-manager] Metisse implements user interface façades, a system that provides users with simple ways to adapt, reconfigure, and recombine existing graphical interfaces, through the use of direct manipulation techniques.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] The project was founded by Havoc Pennington, a GNOME developer working for Red Hat in March 2000.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] Widely used open-source Desktop projects, such as GNOME, KDE's Plasma Desktop, and Xfce, are collaborating with the freedesktop.org project.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] In 2006, the project released Portland 1.0 (xdg-utils), a set of common interfaces for desktop environments. freedesktop.org joined the X.Org Foundation in 2019.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] Some of the project's servers are hosted by Portland State University.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] freedesktop.org provides hosting for a number of relevant projects.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] Also, Avahi (a free Zeroconf implementation) started as a fd.o project but has since become a separate project.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] Besides the variables mentioned below, XDG BDS also specifies that users' local binary files may be installed into `$HOME/.local/bin`.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] Systems compliant with the spec are expected to make this directory available in their CLI's `PATH` environment variable.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] The project aims to catch interoperability issues much earlier in the process.
[src:wayland-protocol/freedesktop-org] It is not for legislating formal standards.
[src:wayland-protocol/kwin] KWin can be configured by scripting using QML or QtScript, both of which are based on ECMAScript.
[src:wayland-protocol/kwin] There are many window decorations for KWin, including the current default Breeze (shown below), the previous default Oxygen, Microsoft Windows-like Redmond, and Keramik.
[src:wayland-protocol/kwin] Currently available compositing backends include OpenGL 1.2, OpenGL 2.0, OpenGL 3.1 and OpenGL ES 2.0.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] Mutter was initially a compositing window manager designed and implemented for the X Window System, but then evolved to be a Wayland compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] It became the default window manager in GNOME 3, replacing Metacity, which used GTK for rendering.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] The name "Mutter" is a combination of "Metacity" and "Clutter".
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] Mutter can function as a standalone window manager for GNOME-like desktops, and serves as the primary window manager for the GNOME Shell, which is an integral part of GNOME since version 3.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] Mutter is extensible with plug-ins, and supports numerous visual effects.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] GNOME Shell is written as a plug-in to Mutter.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] Muffin is a fork of Mutter by the Linux Mint team for their Cinnamon desktop environment.
[src:wayland-protocol/mutter-software] Cinnamon's shell, a fork of GNOME Shell, is written as a plugin for Muffin.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Wayland is developed by a group of volunteers initially led by Kristian Høgsberg as a free and open-source community-driven project with the aim of replacing the X Window System with a secure and simpler windowing system for Linux and other Unix-like operating systems.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The project's source code is published under the terms of the MIT License, a permissive free software license.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland project also develops an implementation of a Wayland compositor called *Weston*.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland compositor looks through its scenegraph to determine which window should receive the event.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The scenegraph corresponds to what is on screen and the Wayland compositor understands the transformations that it may have applied to the elements in the scenegraph.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Thus, the Wayland compositor can pick the right window and transform the screen coordinates to window local coordinates, by applying the inverse transformations.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The types of transformation that can be applied to a window are only restricted to what the compositor can do, as long as it can compute the inverse transformation for the input events.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] As in the X case, when the client receives the event, it updates the UI in response.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] But in the Wayland case, the rendering happens by the client via EGL, and the client just sends a request to the compositor to indicate the region that was updated.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland compositor collects damage requests from its clients and then re-composites the screen.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The compositor can then directly issue an ioctl to schedule a pageflip with KMS.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland Display Server project was created by Red Hat developer Kristian Høgsberg in 2008.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Beginning around 2010, Linux desktop graphics have moved from having "a pile of rendering interfaces... all talking to the X server, which is at the center of the universe" towards putting the Linux kernel and its components (i.e.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Direct Rendering Infrastructure (DRI), Direct Rendering Manager (DRM)) "in the middle", with "window systems like X and Wayland ... off in the corner".
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This will be "a much-simplified graphics system offering more flexibility and better performance".
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland protocol is represented through a .xml file which comes with the Wayland compiler, which can compile the wayland.xml file into relevant C libraries for applications and compositor implementations to use.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The official reference implementation for a Wayland compositor is named Weston.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The project is also developing versions of GTK and Qt that render to Wayland instead of to X.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Most applications are expected to gain support for Wayland through one of these libraries without modification to the application.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Initial versions of Wayland have not provided network transparency, though Høgsberg noted in 2010 that network transparency is possible.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] It was attempted as a Google Summer of Code project in 2011, but was not successful.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Adam Jackson has envisioned providing remote access to a Wayland application by either "pixel-scraping" (like VNC) or getting it to send a "rendering command stream" across the network (as in RDP, SPICE or X11).
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] As of early 2013, Høgsberg was experimenting with network transparency using a proxy Wayland server which sends compressed images to the real compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In August 2017, GNOME saw the first such pixel-scraping VNC server implementation under Wayland.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In modern Wayland compositors, network transparency is handled in an xdg-desktop-portal implementation that implements the RemoteDesktop portal.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Note that xdg-desktop-portal is not Flatpak or Wayland-specific, and can be used with alternative packaging systems and windowing systems.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In the Wayland protocol architecture, a client and a compositor communicate through the Wayland protocol using the reference implementation libraries.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland protocol follows a client–server model in which clients are the graphical applications requesting the display of pixel buffers on the screen, and the server (compositor) is the service provider controlling the display of these buffers.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] While the low-level layer was written manually in C, the high-level layer is automatically generated from a description of the elements of the protocol stored in XML format.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Every time the protocol description in this XML file changes, the C source code that implements the protocol can be regenerated to include the new changes, allowing a very flexible, extensible and error-proof protocol.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The reference implementation of Wayland protocol is split in two libraries: a library to be used by Wayland clients called `libwayland-client` and a library to be used by Wayland compositors called `libwayland-server`.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland protocol is described as an "asynchronous object-oriented protocol".
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] *Object-oriented* means that the services offered by the compositor are presented as a series of *objects* living on the same compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Each object implements an *interface* which has a name, a number of methods (called *requests*) as well as several associated *events*.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Every request and event has zero or more arguments, each one with a name and a data type.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The protocol is *asynchronous* in the sense that requests do not have to wait for synchronized replies or ACKs, avoiding round-trip delay time and achieving improved performance.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland clients can make a request (a method invocation) on some object if the object's interface supports that request.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The client must also supply the required data for the arguments of such request.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This is the way the clients request services from the compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The compositor in turn sends information back to the client by causing the object to emit events (probably with arguments too).
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] These events can be emitted by the compositor as a response to a certain request, or asynchronously, subject to the occurrence of internal events (such as one from an input device) or state changes.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The error conditions are also signaled as events by the compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] For a client to be able to make a request to an object, it first needs to tell the server the ID number it will use to identify that object.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] There are two types of objects in the compositor: global objects and non-global objects.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Global objects are advertised by the compositor to the clients when they are created (and also when they are destroyed), while non-global objects are usually created by other objects that already exist as part of their functionality.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The interfaces and their requests and events are the core elements that define the Wayland protocol.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Each version of the protocol includes a set of interfaces, along with their requests and events, which are expected to be in any Wayland compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Optionally, a Wayland compositor may define and implement its own interfaces that support new requests and events, thereby extending functionality beyond the core protocol.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] To facilitate changes to the protocol, each interface contains a "version number" attribute in addition to its name; this attribute allows for distinguishing variants of the same interface.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Each Wayland compositor exposes not only what interfaces are available, but also the supported versions of those interfaces.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The interfaces of the current version of Wayland protocol are defined in the file protocol/wayland.xml of the Wayland source code.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This is an XML file that lists the existing interfaces in the current version, along with their requests, events and other attributes.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This set of interfaces is the minimum required to be implemented by any Wayland compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] A typical Wayland client session starts by opening a connection to the compositor using the wl_display object.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This is a special local object that represents the connection and does not live within the server.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] By using its interface the client can request the wl_registry global object from the compositor, where all the global object names live, and bind those that the client is interested in.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Usually the client binds at least a wl_compositor object from where it will request one or more wl_surface objects to show the application output on the display.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] A Wayland compositor can define and export its own additional interfaces.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This feature is used to extend the protocol beyond the basic functionality provided by the core interfaces, and has become the standard way to implement Wayland protocol extensions.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Certain compositors can choose to add custom interfaces to provide specialized or unique features.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland reference compositor, Weston, used them to implement new experimental interfaces as a testbed for new concepts and ideas, some of which later became part of the core protocol (such as wl_subsurface interface added in Wayland 1.4).
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] XDG-Shell protocol (see freedesktop.org for XDG) is an extended way to manage surfaces under Wayland compositors (not only Weston).
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The traditional way to manipulate (maximize, minimize, fullscreen, etc.) surfaces is to use the `wl_shell_*()` functions, which are part of the core Wayland protocol and live in libwayland-client, however are now deprecated.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] An implementation of the xdg-shell protocol, on the contrary, is supposed to be provided by the Wayland compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] So you will find the <xdg-shell-client-protocol.h> header in the Weston source tree.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] xdg_shell is a protocol aimed to substitute wl_shell in the long term, but will not be part of the Wayland core protocol.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] It starts as a non-stable API, aimed to be used as a development place at first, and once features are defined as required by several desktop shells, it can be finally made stable.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] It provides mainly two new interfaces: xdg_surface and xdg_popup.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The xdg_surface interface implements a desktop-style window that can be moved, resized, maximized, etc.; it provides a request for creating child/parent relationship.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The xdg_popup interface implements a desktop-style popup/menu; an xdg_popup is always transient for another surface, and also has implicit grab.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] IVI-Shell is an extension to the Wayland core protocol, targeting in-vehicle infotainment (IVI) devices.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland protocol does not include a rendering API.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Instead, Wayland follows a *direct rendering* model, in which the client must render the window contents to a buffer shareable with the compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] For that purpose, the client can choose to do all the rendering by itself, use a rendering library like Cairo or OpenGL, or rely on the rendering engine of high-level widget libraries with Wayland support, such as Qt or GTK.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The client can also optionally use other specialized libraries to perform specific tasks, such as Freetype for font rendering.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The resulting buffer with the rendered window contents are stored in a wl_buffer object.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The internal type of this object is implementation dependent.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The only requirement is that the content data must be shareable between the client and the compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] If the client uses a software (CPU) renderer and the result is stored in the system memory, then client and compositor can use shared memory to implement the buffer communication without extra copies.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland protocol already natively provides this kind of shared memory buffer through the wl_shm and wl_shm_pool interfaces.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The drawback of this method is that the compositor may need to do additional work (usually to copy the shared data to the GPU) to display it, which leads to slower graphics performance.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The most typical case is for the client to render directly into a video memory buffer using a hardware (GPU) accelerated API such as OpenGL, OpenGL ES or Vulkan.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Client and compositor can share this GPU-space buffer using a special handler to reference it.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This method allows the compositor to avoid the extra data copy through itself of the main memory buffer client-to-compositor-to-GPU method, resulting in faster graphics performance, and is therefore the preferred one.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The compositor can further optimize the composition of the final scene to be shown on the display by using the same hardware acceleration API as an API client.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] When rendering is completed in a shared buffer, the Wayland client should instruct the compositor to present the rendered contents of the buffer on the display.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] For this purpose, the client binds the buffer object that stores the rendered contents to the surface object, and sends a "commit" request to the surface, transferring the effective control of the buffer to the compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Then the client waits for the compositor to release the buffer (signaled by an event) if it wants to reuse the buffer to render another frame, or it can use another buffer to render the new frame, and, when the rendering is finished, bind this new buffer to the surface and commit its contents.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The procedure used for rendering, including the number of buffers involved and their management, is entirely under the client control.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] is a separate, additional feature in X, while Wayland merges display server and compositor as a single function.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] , which in X is a separate client-side process.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Compositing is optional in X, but mandatory in Wayland.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Compositing in X is "active"; that is, the compositor must fetch all pixel data, which introduces latency.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In Wayland, compositing is "passive", which means the compositor receives pixel data directly from clients.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The X server itself is able to perform rendering, although it can also be instructed to display a rendered window sent by a client.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In contrast, Wayland does not expose any API for rendering, but delegates to clients such tasks (including the rendering of fonts, widgets, etc.).
