[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] although some extensions have been developed trying to mitigate it.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] although multiple popular Linux distributions now allow the X server to be run without root privileges.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] that was designed at its core to run over a network.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] XWayland is an X Server running as a Wayland client, and thus is capable of displaying native X11 client applications in a Wayland compositor environment.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This is similar to the way XQuartz runs X applications in macOS's native windowing system.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The goal of XWayland is to facilitate the transition from X Window System to Wayland environments, providing a way to run unported applications in the meantime.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] XWayland was mainlined into X.Org Server version 1.16.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Widget toolkits such as Qt 5 and GTK 3 can switch their graphical back-end at run time, allowing users to choose at load time whether they want to run the application over X or over Wayland.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Qt 5 provides the `-platform` command-line option to that effect, whereas GTK 3 lets users select the desired GDK back-end by setting the `GDK_BACKEND` Unix environment variable.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Display servers that implement the Wayland display server protocol are also called *Wayland compositors* because they additionally perform the task of a compositing window manager.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] A library called **wlroots** is a modular Wayland implementation that functions as a base for several compositors.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Weston is a Wayland compositor previously developed as the reference implementation of the protocol by the Wayland project.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] It is written in C and released under the MIT License.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Weston officially supports only Linux due to dependencies on kernel-specific features such as kernel mode-setting (KMS), the Graphics Execution Manager (GEM), and udev.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] On Linux, it handles input via evdev and buffer management via Generic Buffer Management (GBM).
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] A prototype port for FreeBSD was announced in 2013.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The compositor supports High-bandwidth Digital Content Protection (HDCP) and uses GEM to share buffers between applications and the compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] It features a plug-in architecture with "shells" that provide elements like docks and panels.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Applications are responsible for rendering their own window decorations.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Weston supports rendering via OpenGL ES or the pixman library for software rendering.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The full OpenGL stack is avoided to prevent pulling in GLX and other X Window System dependencies.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] A remote desktop interface for Weston was proposed in 2013 by a developer from RealVNC.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Raspberry Pi Holdings in collaboration with Collabora released Maynard.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Weston code for handling input devices (keyboards, pointers, touch screens, etc.) was split into its own separate library, called *libinput*, for which support was first merged in Weston 1.5.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Libinput handles input devices for multiple Wayland compositors and also provides a generic X.Org Server input driver.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] It aims to provide one implementation for multiple Wayland compositors with a common way to handle input events while minimizing the amount of custom input code compositors need to include. libinput provides device detection (via udev), device handling, input device event processing and abstraction.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Version 1.0 of libinput followed version 0.21, and included support for tablets, button sets and touchpad gestures.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] This version will maintain stable API/ABI.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] As GNOME/GTK and KDE Frameworks 5 have mainlined the required changes, Fedora 22 will replace X.Org's evdev and Synaptics drivers with libinput.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] With version 1.16, the X.Org Server obtained support for the libinput library in form of a wrapper called xf86-input-libinput.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Wayland Security Module is a proposition that resembles the Linux Security Module interface found in the Linux kernel.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Some applications (especially the ones related to accessibility) require privileged capabilities that should work across different Wayland compositors.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Currently, applications under Wayland are generally unable to perform any sensitive tasks such as taking screenshots or injecting input events without going through xdg-desktop-portal or obtaining privileged access to the system.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The security model forced by Wayland also creates mouse position problems when attempting to type text in many games.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Wayland Security Module is a way to delegate security decisions within the compositor to a centralized security decision engine.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland protocol is designed to be simple so that additional protocols and interfaces need to be defined and implemented to achieve a holistic windowing system.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] While many graphical toolkits already fully support Wayland, the developers of the graphical shells are cooperating with the Wayland developers to create the necessary additional interfaces.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Most major Linux distributions default to using Wayland.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Desktop environments that have been ported from X11 to Wayland include GNOME, KDE Plasma and Enlightenment.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Currently, Xfce is also developing a Wayland compositor.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Kristian Høgsberg, a Linux graphics and X.Org developer who previously worked on AIGLX and DRI2, started Wayland as a spare-time project in 2008 while working for Red Hat.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Other early prominent developers for Wayland include Daniel Stone, Peter Hutterer, and Pekka Paalanen.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In October 2010, Wayland became a freedesktop.org project.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The developer mailing list was migrated at that time to *wayland-devel*, which as of 2026 is hosted via GNU Mailman.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] The Wayland client and server libraries were initially released under the MIT License, while the reference compositor Weston and some example clients used the GNU General Public License version 2.
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Later, all the GPL code was relicensed under the MIT license "to make it easier to move code between the reference implementation and the actual libraries".
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] In 2015 it was discovered that the license text used by Wayland was a slightly different and older version of the MIT license, and the license text was updated to the current version used by the X.Org project (known as MIT Expat License).
[src:wayland-protocol/wayland-protocol] Wayland works with all Mesa-compatible drivers with DRI2 support as well as Android drivers via the Hybris project.
